    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-12-12T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-12-12T02:00:00-05:00" n="124"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d124">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.001/423: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Chefoo</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Roberts</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chefoo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-12-12T15:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 12, 1938—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 12—6 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6. Referring to the Department’s telegram No. 2, November 23, 8 p.m.,<note n="37"
                        xml:id="d124fn37">See telegram No. 305 of the same date to the Counselor of
                        Embassy in China, <ref target="#pg_96">p. 96</ref>.</note> concerning
                    interference with American commerce. The Japanese Consul has informed Consulate
                    that the Japanese Navy, effective December 5, removed restrictions on the
                    shipment of foodstuffs, clothing, shoes and fuel from Chefoo to the interior and
                    coastal ports of Shantung. The Japanese Naval authorities state that “fuel”
                    includes kerosene, gasoline and oil products and that shipments of these
                    articles may be made to guerrilla controlled interior destinations without
                    restrictions. This action removes the major restriction on American trade in
                    this consular district.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping, Chungking, Tsingtao and Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Roberts</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
